ntional wisdom would suggest.Building on a large data set of the demographics of redrawn districts and subsequent congressional elections, Seabrook looks less at the who and how of gerrymandering and considers more closely the practical effects of partisan redistricting plans. He finds that the redrawing of districts often results in no detrimental effect for district-level competition. Short-term benefits in terms of capturing seats are sometimes achieved but long-term results are uncertain. By focusing on the end results rather than on the motivations of political actors, Seabrook seeks to recast the political debate about the importance of partisanship. He supports institutionalizing metrics for competitiveness that would prove more threatening to all incumbents no matter their party affiliation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aApportionment (Election law)zUnited States. 0aGerrymanderingzUnited States. 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106658710 cprintz978150170531140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501707797?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501707797423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501707797/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK